From Murray Altheim Subject Re to fix TRACKBALL In article writes The trackbal on my no longer moves in the horizontal When I called the nearest Authorized Apple Service person I was told that it probably needed replacing and that would cost me over Ouch Can anyone recommend a less expensive way to fix this problem One strange symptom of the problem is that when I take the ball out of the socket and shine a light into the hole I can make the cursor move horizontally by moving the wheel with my finger it works fine that way but won't work if I turn off the Any suggestions or comments Ben Roy a poor college Ben Since you're obviously adept enough to understand how the trackball works the only thing short of repairing it that I can think of is a thorough cleaning of all the parts and then checking for the proper placement of the little blue Since they aren't fixed in position on their stainless steel pins you might try sliding them into a slightly different On my PowerBook I can slide them almost completely out of contact with the In fact one of the notes from sumex on fixing the trackball advocates sliding the roller so that its edge contacts the ball not the center cylindrical I've done this with my and it does seem to improve the feel but needs to be adjusted from time to I just popped open one of our office's and while there isn't as much latitude for movement one could still adjust the roller If your is the same it might I would suspect the most likely culprit to be a slippery blue If you can take it out clean it with a mild soapy solution or isopropyl Also be sure the ball is grease If you drop the ball in minus the retaining ring roll the ball and see if it is actually causing the axle to If all this still doesn't solve it then maybe a new one is in It could be an electrical connection in which case replacement would be But my experience with both mice and trackballs has been that dirt has been the normal problem not an electrical Hope this helps Murray Murray A